      "rationale": "Three-level GCI study yielded 3.2% fine-to-medium GCI for hemolysis index at worst-case operating point. Monotonic convergence confirmed. Medium mesh (6.4 M cells) selected for production runs as cost-accuracy optimum."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Experimental boundary conditions (flow rate, rotational speed, fluid properties) documented and traceable; uncertainty in test conditions quantified.",
      "rationale": "FDA experimental dataset provides fully documented boundary conditions. Flow rate uncertainty ±0.05 L/min, speed uncertainty ±10 RPM. Blood analog (glycerol-water) viscosity measured at test temperature. All conditions within COU operating envelope."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Quantitative comparison metric (e.g., E% or GCI-normalized error) computed for all primary QoIs; statistical agreement assessed across the full operating envelope of 5 flow-speed combinations.",
      "rationale": "Output comparison was performed for three of the five required flow-speed operating points. The two highest-flow operating points (7 L/min and 8 L/min at 3000 RPM) were excluded from quantitative comparison due to unavailability of experimental hemolysis measurements at those conditions in the FDA dataset. Qualitative trend agreement was noted for these points based on extrapolation from adjacent conditions, but no quantitative error metric was computed. The assessment team judged this gap acceptable given the conservative nature of the RH < 1 acceptance criterion; however, a formal Gradation 2 output comparison requires coverage of all COU-relevant operating points."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Primary QoI (relative hemolysis index) directly maps to the clinical decision criterion; secondary QoIs (wall shear stress, exposure time) are mechanistically linked.",
      "rationale": "RHI is the direct regulatory acceptance criterion. Wall shear stress and scalar transport exposure time are intermediate QoIs used in the power-law hemolysis model; both are physically motivated and traceable to published hemolysis damage models (Giersiepen et al., Heuser-Opitz)."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Validation geometry, fluid properties, and operating range sufficiently similar to COU device and conditions to support extrapolation.",
      "rationale": "Validation performed on FDA generic centrifugal pump — same geometry class as COU device. Blood analog fluid properties match within 4% of whole blood viscosity at physiological shear rates. Operating range (2–6 L/min, 2500–3500 RPM) overlaps COU envelope. Geometric similarity ratio 1:1 (same pump). Relevance judged high."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
